According to Cecilia, the abortion controversy within the Catholic church and Liberia is an issue of a woman's right to make decisions regarding her body and her health. (p. 43). Cecilia also presents tangible stories of women convincing their husbands that family planning is their god given right (Andalus) that can be very empowering for a woman (p. 81-90). In one example, a woman went back to school after becoming an influencer initially to regularize her own pregnancy, then return to work, and next share her story. (p. 89). An interesting point is when Cecilia heads back to MND Hospital in Chester to see the two women Cecilia began helping while there previously. She tells us that Anel is still not having the baby since she proposed she needed to travel outside Monrovia to Medihuge clinic in the westcoast to get treatment, rather than speak with the health professionals at MND. When Anel came upon a new health professional who suggested she could buy herbs from the health center to help relax the contraction, this professional's suggestion rendered Anel knowledgeable to make a decision. Antinette by this time had undoubtedly had her baby and passed away. Cecilia discusses how this might happen given we are dealing with African women, who don't have the right explanation to abortion and the availability of abortion drugs at the health center.
